<title type="html"><![CDATA[Composite artifact rendering]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=2917&amp;p=21842#p21842"><![CDATA[
No, I did not mean anything against your filter, on the other side, it really rocks all the way, and I like using it pretty much. What is great is that you can "attenuate" the things, and it really looks like original once the frame merging is enabled (however I think it really looks horrible with frame merging disabled, but that's not an issue because you can just enable it).<br />However, it's just a different philosophy over a filter such as 2xSal : NTSC filters goals to have the image look like it does on a TV, while 2xSal try to stretch the image wile keeping nice and round graphics. I think both rocks, and it's a very good thing you can choose between both when you want to play a game, and that is what makes emulation a good thing.<br /><br />It's just like the 8-sprite limitation, you can just enable it and make sure your emulators emulate accurately your NES by keeping it's original look (and maybe some games would actually rely on it), or turn it off and take the advantage to play games with enhanced graphics with all anoying flickering almost removed, but some games will look weird with that.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Sun Feb 04, 2007 12:43 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
