<author><name><![CDATA[blargg]]></name></author>
<updated>2007-02-04T11:52:02-07:00</updated>
<published>2007-02-04T11:52:02-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=2917&amp;p=21839#p21839</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=2917&amp;p=21839#p21839"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Composite artifact rendering]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=2917&amp;p=21839#p21839"><![CDATA[
The only objective measure of NES emulation is how close it is to a NES connected to a late 1980s/early 1990s TV. Enhancements are subjective, and people differ on which ones they like/dislike. There's also no end to how much time you can spend enhancing something, since it's just another word for making changes that are subjectively pleasing or helpful.<br /><br />My main goal with the NTSC filter is approximating the image on a TV. For people who desire the original look, it's the best we've got short of using a TV. For people who don't like that, I provide many adjustments to reduce some of the composite effects, like pixel artifacts, blurring, fringing, and color bleed (which is the most helpful thing to leave enabled, in my opinion). Still, I don't pretend that it's superior to any other filter as far as how pleasing it looks, so I don't mind what filter someone uses most.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Sun Feb 04, 2007 11:52 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
